description.narrative: By end 2021, sanitation structures in the targeted provinces have the human and material resources to enable them to offer preventive and curative nutrition services to women, adolescents and children under five years of age, which contributes to Community-Based Management Of Acute Malnutrition, Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Infant And Young Child Feeding, Micronutrients, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Nutrition â€“ General. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 2. By the end of 2022, adolescents, pregnant and breastfeeding women, mothers and children aged 0-5 years make greater use of quality nutritional services and adopt adequate nutrition and feeding practices in 15 provinces.

description.narrative: To date, 825 i.e., 47% of the 1,766 national functioning health facilities have been equipped with materials and supplies (medical and nutritional) for quality treatment of severe acute malnutrition. By the end of November 2021,283,694children with SAM had been admitted and treated in health facilities, with an average recovery rate of 94.3%. This required skills on the Integrated Management of Acute Malnutrition (IMAM);according to the protocol and UNICEF supported training of 314 health workers i.e., 100% of the annual target and provided financial support to maintain high quality workforce with 93 additional health workers in targeted health facilities. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:22/01/2022
